text_answer.content: While this passage in general is ok, I would not feel comfortable speaking with a student about "transgender" students as referenced in this article. And you KNOW that would come up in the conversation, whether it be a question of "what is transgender" or whether they feel it is singling out that student group. When speaking about student groups that would use peer counseling, can we rewrite that portion of the passage to be a little more "generic" and not touch on topics that would generate an entirely different conversation? As it stands, alot of student groups at any different time could need peer counseling for various reasons. Our job is not to hold a discussion on those reasons, but to help them learn how to read and translate passages. (The suicide and transgender conversations would be very touchy for tutors and these passages don't need to encourage that. Also, students will go home and tell their families about these passages and we don't want to be questioned about why those subjects came up in a tutoring session). Just saying...please consider a revision in that portion of the passage re: why students would need peer counseling and avoid controversial subjects that don't need to be addressed in a tutoring session at Huntington. Also please remove the word transgender from the vocabulary section. Thanks!

text_answer.content: This passage needs to be REWORKED!! There is incorrect information and various inconsistencies that make this a poorly done passage. Mostly it relates to the distances in the atmosphere of regular lightning and sprite lightning. Some places in the passage list the distance in measurement in KM and some places in MILES. (i.e. at the beginning of paragraph 2 states that the mesosphere is 50 miles above the ground. The vocabulary question #3 (which is the sentence that mesosphere correctly answers) states that it's 50-80 KM above the earth. The correct distance is 50-80 KILOMETERS. The vocab question #3 (uses mesosphere for the answer) doesn't match the units stated in the passage. Honestly, students can relate to MILES more than kilometers and perhaps measurements should not be listed  in metric units.  I would check the accuracy of this entire article and rewrite it. Also, there's aLOT of numbers, measurements, etc in here for students to plow through. That makes it more boring and more tedious to read. This is a challenge for this grade level.Either way this should be placed later in the curriculum after a good rework.

Very soft yes on unverifiable information. Information Simon and Curie is a little tough to track down. I believe I was able to verify that they did exist, but the most recent thing I could find about them is their Facebook page from from 6 years ago. Most of the references that Google brought back were from the game SOMA, which isn't making it easier to find details about the robots described here. Even if what's written here is accurate, I'm sure there are more recent examples that fit the needs of the passage better. Shimon was easier to verify, but even then the most recent update is a press release on their website from 2020.
Though fairly subtle, this feels like I'm being sold on the idea of robotics. I was fine with it in my initial read, so it's a soft yes on bias. I only realized it as I was trying to find an alternative inference and realized how overwhelmingly positive this passage is about this topic. This also doesn't take into account that the inference itself is biased and not supported by the passage (see below).
Side note: this passage directly contradicts all the passages which discuss the impact AI has on the work force and how human creativity is going to continue to be a commodity.

For the inference, D is a stretch. Paragraph 1 says "robots are taking on increasingly complex tasks that were once performed only by humans." This quote is open ended enough not to suggest either replacing or complementing human workers, but that resulting in the conclusion given is also not being supported. Yes, the passage explores how robots work alongside humans, but it's fairly obvious that some of these roles, especially the Robear, could easily be done by humans.
I'm not seeing an alternative inference, which could mean this passage needs another pass.

All the vocabulary sentences are just the definitions of their respective words or include the definition.
Diaspora is defined wrong. It's just the general dispersal of a group of people to new areas and doesn't include any elements of maintaining their cultural connections. That aspect is implied, I guess, but it's not technically a part of the definition proper. I'm also a little wary of the word due to its significant attachment to the Jewish population specifically, but it's probably fine. After reading the passage, I get the confusion as 'diaspora' and 'diaspora communities' have subtly different meanings. The vocabulary sentence is more in line with the later.

For the inference, although the passage doesn't say 'immigrant families' directly, answer A is literally the main idea of the concluding paragraph.
I could see B as a possible answer. It is a bit of a stretch, but the passage makes a reasonable deal about how traditional clothing practices go hand-in-hand with the cultural traditions. If one is weakening, it's reasonable to conclude that the other is as well.
Alternatively, "South Korean wedding dresses incorporate the color red to promote good fortune." - This combines two distinct facts into a logical conclusion.
